<DOC><DOCNO> AP880622-0130 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-88 1226EST</FILEID><FIRST>r w AM-BRF--Atlantic-Climate     06-22 0124</FIRST><SECOND>AM-BRF--Atlantic-Climate,120</SECOND><NOTE>For release at 6:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE><HEAD>Scientists To Study Atlantic-Climate Effects</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Scientists from three nations will spend Julyand August cruising the Atlantic Ocean to learn how that body ofwater affects climate.   The research vessel Mt. Mitchell will begin the cruise fromNorfolk, Va., in July, traveling to Bermuda, Iceland, the Azoresand Barbados during the research effort, which ends in September.   Aboard will be meteorologists from the United States, Canada andthe United Kingdom, according to the National Oceanic andAtmospheric Administration, which is sponsoring the cruise.   The aim is to measure the interaction of the ocean andatmosphere, particularly effects on chemicals which may affectweather or climate, including carbon dioxide, sulfur and nitrogencompounds.</TEXT></DOC>